- Test the Theravada hybrid more carefully. The path involves conditioned effort leading to an unconditioned result. Is this a genuine combination of production and removal, or is there a single dominant resolution with the other playing a subordinate role? Close reading of the Visuddhimagga's treatment of the transition from the last conditioned insight knowledge to the supramundane path moment may clarify.
- Ask dual-trained practitioners whether changing efficacy resolution changes their felt relationship to effort, time, and failure. A practitioner trained in both Theravada vipassana (production-leaning) and Dzogchen (removal-leaning) could report whether switching frameworks changes what effort feels like from the inside.
- Protocol improvement: before using any contemplative method as a thinking lens, name the efficacy resolution it presupposes. The Dogen lens used here presupposes the identity resolution, which may have biased the analysis toward treating separation as error. Future runs should alternate between lenses that assume different resolutions to check whether the model holds under each.

